  "prompt": "In which cases can an arrested foreigner request prosecution in their homeland?",
  "response": "The ability of an arrested foreigner to request prosecution in their homeland depends on several factors:\n\n1. Bilateral agreements\n- Some countries have extradition treaties\n- Specific agreements may allow transfer of criminal proceedings\n\n2. Diplomatic relations\n- Strong diplomatic ties can facilitate transfer requests\n- Mutual legal assistance treaties might support such transfers\n\n3. Type of crime\n- Less serious offenses might be more likely to be transferred\n- Serious international crimes typically require prosecution where committed\n\n4. Home country's legal system\n- Must have compatible legal standards\n- Willingness to accept prosecution responsibility\n\n5. International conventions\n- Some multilateral agreements facilitate criminal prosecution transfers\n- Depends on specific treaty provisions\n\n6. Jurisdiction factors\n- Location of crime\n- Nationality of offender\n- Severity of potential punishment\n\n7. Individual circumstances\n- Personal circumstances of the arrested individual\n- Potential humanitarian considerations\n\nThe specific process and likelihood of transfer vary significantly between different countries and depend on unique circumstances of each case. Legal consultation with diplomatic representatives is recommended for precise guidance.",
